<subSubSection id="DCCEABA0FFFF16071497FCE9FE63F81A" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" type="description">
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497FCE9FBDCFCD2" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" box="[199,1082,834,861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF16071497FCE9FEBFFCD3" bold="true" box="[199,345,834,860]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Description.</emphasis>
Female (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF16071591FCE8FDF8FCD2" box="[449,542,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1953,1977]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,356,1922]" captionTargetId="figure-112@2.[151,1436,345,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Dorsal habitus of new species of Hexarhopalus. A. H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female; B. H. (H.) tianbaoyanensis sp. nov., male; C. Same, female; D. H. (H.) yeziyangi sp. nov., male; E. Same, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598175/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Figs 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF1607167AFCE8FDDDFCD2" box="[554,571,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">2</figureCitation>
): Body oval, strongly convex, black and dull.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497FCCCFB30FB4A" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
Head (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF16071542FCCCFE8DFC0E" box="[274,363,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) transverse, widest across compound eyes. Vertex covered with large punctures and each puncture bearing a short, thin seta. Genae and epistoma covered with denser and smaller punctures and setae relative to punctures and setae on vertex. Labrum black, narrower than epistoma, covered in apical portion with sparse bristles of medium length. Antennal tubercles weakly prominent, antenna (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF160717D9FC78FC06FC62" box="[905,992,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
) longer than pronotum, club composed of four apical antennomeres. Relative lengths of antennomeres: 0.37: 0.22: 0.67: 0.63: 0.51: 0.50: 0.50: 0.48: 0.46: 0.43: 0.66; relative widths of antennomeres: 0.34: 0.28: 0.31: 0.31: 0.32: 0.32: 0.44: 0.51: 0.48: 0.51: 0.53. Antennomere I slightly expanded; antennomere II shortest, wider than long; antennomere III about as long as antennomere XI, more than 2.5× as long as antennomere II, antennomeres IV–VI similar, shorter than antennomere III, antennomere VII expanded near apex and nearly trapezoidal, antennomere VIII about as long as wide, antennomeres IX–X wider than long, antennomere XI with apex rounded, antennomeres VIII–XI distinctly expanded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497FB64FC7BFAF6" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF16071515FB64FE7BFB66" box="[325,413,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) slightly longer than wide, widest at middle; dorsal surface covered with dense small punctures and short setae; disc with distinct irregular rugosity; mediolongitudinal sulcus shallow but visible, almost as long as length of pronotum, and without irregular rugosity; pronotal groove thin and not obvious basally, absent in anterior part, and wide and shallow at lateral margin (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF160716B4FA90FCDDFADA" box="[740,827,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Prosternum distinctly raised before procoxae, surface wrinkled with sparse short setae; apex of prosternal process rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497FA28FE17FA6A" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Elytra ovoid, about 1.3× longer than wide in dorsal view, humerus strongly narrowed, widest at apical 1/3, disc with regular rows of strong foveolate punctures and strong irregular rugosity; scutellum transverse, nearly triangular; wings completely reduced.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497FA44FB46F9FA" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Metaventrite and abdomen finely covered with short thin setae and dense small punctures; median sulcus distinct, extending from anterior margin to ca. 2/3 of metaventrite length.Abdominal ventrite I longest, about as long as combined lengths of ventrites III and IV; ventrite II longer than metaventrite III; metaventrites III and IV distinctly concave; ventrite V about as long as combined lengths of ventrites III and IV, apex rounded.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497F9D4FDFEF88A" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Femora claviform medially, strongly expanded in distal halves; all tibiae covered with brown setae apically; pro- and mesotibiae slightly curved, metatibia straight; tarsomeres simple, apical pro- and mesotarsomeres about as long as combined lengths of proximal four tarsomeres, apical metatarsomere slightly shorter than combined lengths of proximal three metatarsomeres.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497F8A4FA62F8C2" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
Posterior margin of ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF1607161DF8A4FD41F8A6" box="[589,679,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
) rounded and covered with sparse long setae. Spiculum (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF1607116AF8A4FA72F8A6" box="[1338,1428,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
) nearly stright, apex rounded and slightly dilated. Apex of ovipositor (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFFF160717CEF898FC15F8C2" box="[926,1011,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1958,1982]" captionTargetBox="[166,1416,381,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-99@3.[151,1436,381,1935]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) ferreri sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; E. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
) with two long and two short setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497F8FCFA65F8FE" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" box="[199,1411,1878,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
Measurements: BL 
<quantity id="532C55CEFFFF160715F3F8FCFDEFF8FE" box="[419,521,1879,1905]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.89" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="18.9">18.9 mm</quantity>
, HL 
<quantity id="532C55CEFFFF16071610F8FDFD7EF8FE" box="[576,664,1878,1905]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
, HW 
<quantity id="532C55CEFFFF16071689F8FCFCD7F8FE" box="[729,817,1879,1905]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="3.7">3.7 mm</quantity>
, PL 6.0 mm, PW 
<quantity id="532C55CEFFFF160717A7F8FDFBA9F8FE" box="[1015,1103,1878,1905]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="5.6">5.6 mm</quantity>
, EL 
<quantity id="532C55CEFFFF160710D3F8FCFB0FF8FE" box="[1155,1257,1879,1905]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.04" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" unit="mm" value="10.4">10.4 mm</quantity>
, EW 8.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16071497F8D0FE63F81A" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" box="[199,389,1915,1941]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Male. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DCCEABA0FFFF16041497F835FC8EFECE" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="594" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFFF16041497F835FC8EFECE" blockId="1.[151,1437,762,2013]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,321]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="594" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF16071497F835FE28F837" bold="true" box="[199,462,1950,1976]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species differs from all other species of 
<taxonomicName id="53D483A8FFFF160717ACF834FB7CF836" authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1891" box="[1020,1178,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF160717ACF834FB7CF836" box="[1020,1178,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">Hexarhopalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
owing to the strong irregular rugosity of the elytra. However, 
<taxonomicName id="53D483A8FFFF16071606F868FD12F852" authority="Jiang &amp; Zhou &amp; Liu &amp; Huang &amp; Chen, 2022" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Zhou &amp; Liu &amp; Huang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2022" box="[598,756,1987,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferreri" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Hexarhopalus">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF16071606F868FD94F853" box="[598,626,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF160716D1F868FD7BF853" box="[641,669,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF160716FCF868FD12F852" box="[684,756,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">ferreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF160716ABF868FCB2F852" bold="true" box="[763,852,1987,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="BD939942FFFF160716ABF868FCB2F852" box="[763,852,1987,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is more or less similar to 
<taxonomicName id="53D483A8FFFF16041023F868FE2AFF3E" authority="Jiang, Li, Ji, Engel, &amp; Wang, 2021" authorityName="Jiang, Li, Ji, Engel, &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="594" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis" subGenus="Hexarhopalus">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF16071023F868FB69F853" box="[1139,1167,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF160710CEF868FB5CF853" box="[1182,1210,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFF16071099F868FAB5F853" box="[1225,1363,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="593">yunnanensis</emphasis>
Jiang, Li, Ji, Engel, &amp; Wang, 2021
</taxonomicName>
also from Yunnan and 
<taxonomicName id="53D483A8FFFC1604169BFF3CFC47FF3E" box="[715,929,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="594" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculatu" subGenus="Hexarhopalus">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC1604169BFF3CFD01FF3F" box="[715,743,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC160416A6FF3CFCF4FF3F" box="[758,786,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC16041771FF3CFC47FF3E" box="[801,929,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">tuberculatu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s (Pic, 1928) from 
<collectingCountry id="ECC3B8BBFFFC16041020FF3CFB4FFF3E" box="[1136,1193,151,177]" name="Laos" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">Laos</collectingCountry>
, with all three species having an overall oval profile to the body. Nonetheless, these species can be easily separated on the basis of their different integumental sculpturing on the elytra: the elytra of 
<taxonomicName id="53D483A8FFFC16041710FF74FBC7FF76" box="[832,1057,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="594" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculatus" subGenus="Hexarhopalus">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC16041710FF74FCBAFF77" box="[832,860,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC1604173BFF74FC60FF77" box="[875,902,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC160417C6FF74FBC7FF76" box="[918,1057,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">tuberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are covered with differently sized tubercles, the elytra of 
<taxonomicName id="53D483A8FFFC160415CEFEA8FD67FE93" authorityName="Jiang, Li, Ji, Engel, &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2021" box="[414,641,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="594" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis" subGenus="Hexarhopalus">
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC160415CEFEA8FE5CFE93" box="[414,442,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC1604159BFEA8FE00FE93" box="[459,486,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFFC160415A7FEA8FD67FE93" box="[503,641,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="594">yunnanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are covered with a thin irregular rugosity, while the elytra of the new species are modified with strong, convex, and irregular rugosity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
